# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: srgb-colorspace
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The **Adobe RGB (1998) color space** or **opRGB** is a color space developed by Adobe Inc. in 1998.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] It was designed to encompass most of the colors achievable on CMYK color printers, but by using RGB primary colors on a device such as a computer display.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The Adobe RGB (1998) color space encompasses roughly 30% of the visible colors specified by the CIELAB color space – improving upon the gamut of the sRGB color space, primarily in cyan-green hues.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] It was subsequently standardized by the IEC as IEC 61966-2-5:1999 with a name opRGB (optional RGB color space) and is used in HDMI.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Beginning in 1997, Adobe Systems was looking into creating ICC profiles that its consumers could use in conjunction with Photoshop's new color management features.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Since not many applications at the time had any ICC color management, most operating systems did not ship with useful profiles.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Lead developer of Photoshop, Thomas Knoll decided to build an ICC profile around specifications he found in the documentation for the SMPTE 240M standard, the precursor to Rec.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] 709 (but not in primaries: 240M also defined EOTF and thus was display referred, sRGB was created by connecting BT.470 PAL and SMPTE C).
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] SMPTE 240M's gamut is wider than that of the BT.709 gamut and the same as SMPTE ST 170 also known as SMPTE C.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] However, with the release of Photoshop 5.0 nearing, Adobe made the decision to include the profile within the software.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Although users loved the wider range of reproducible colors, those familiar with the SMPTE 240M specifications contacted Adobe, informing the company that it had copied the values that described idealized primaries, not actual standard ones (in a special annex to the standard).
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The real values were much closer to sRGB's, which avid Photoshop consumers did not enjoy as a working environment.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] To make matters worse, Thomas Knoll had made an error when copying the red primary chromaticity coordinates, resulting in an even more inaccurate representation of the SMPTE standard.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] On the other hand red and blue primaries are the same as in PAL and green is the same as in NTSC 1953 (blue is the same as in BT.709 and sRGB).
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Adobe tried numerous tactics to correct the profile, such as correcting the red primary and changing the white point to match that of the CIE Standard Illuminant D50 (though that will also change the primaries and is thus pointless), yet all of the adjustments made CMYK conversion worse than before.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] In the end, Adobe decided to keep the "incorrect" profile, but changed the name to *Adobe RGB (1998)* in order to avoid a trademark search or infringement.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] In Adobe RGB (1998), colors are specified as [*R*,*G*,*B*] triplets, where each of the *R*, *G*, and *B* components have values ranging between 0 and 1.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] When displayed on a monitor, the exact chromaticities of the reference white point [1,1,1], the reference black point [0,0,0], and the primaries ([1,0,0], [0,1,0], and [0,0,1]) are specified.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] To meet the color appearance requirements of the color space, the luminance of the monitor must be 160.00 cd/m2 at the white point, and 0.5557 cd/m2 at the black point, which implies a contrast ratio of 287.9.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Moreover, the black point shall have the same chromaticity as the white point, yet with a luminance equal to 0.34731% of the white point luminance.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The ambient illumination level at the monitor faceplate when the monitor is turned off must be 32 lx.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] As with sRGB, the *RGB* component values in Adobe RGB (1998) are not proportional to the luminances.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Rather, a gamma of approximately 2.2 is assumed, without the linear segment near zero that is present in sRGB.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] In coverage of the CIE 1931 color space the Adobe RGB (1998) color space covers 52.1%.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] where *XKYKZK* and *XWYWZW* are reference display black and white points in the table above.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] As was later defined in the IEC standard opYCC uses BT.601 matrix for conversion to YCbCr, that can be full range matrix and limited range matrix.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Display can signal YCC quantization range support and sink can send either one.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] An image in the ICC Profile Connection Space (PCS) is encoded in 24-bit Adobe RGB (1998) color image encoding.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The component values would be clipped to the range [0, 1].
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The resulting component values would be then represented in floating point or integer encodings.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] sRGB is an RGB color space proposed by HP and Microsoft in 1996 to approximate the color gamut of the (then) most common computer display devices (CRTs).
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Adobe RGB (1998) extends into richer cyans and greens than does sRGB – for all levels of luminance.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The two gamuts are often compared in mid-tone values (~50% luminance), but clear differences are evident in shadows (~25% luminance) and highlights (~75% luminance) as well.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] In fact, Adobe RGB (1998) expands its advantages to areas of intense orange, yellow, and magenta regions.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Also, although Adobe RGB (1998) can *theoretically* represent a wider gamut of colors, the color space requires special software and a complex workflow in order to utilize its full range.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Otherwise, the produced colors would be squeezed into a smaller range (making them appear duller) in order to match sRGB's more widely used gamut.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Although the Adobe RGB (1998) working space clearly provides more colors to utilize, another factor to consider when choosing between color spaces is how each space influences the distribution of the image's bit depth.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] Color spaces with larger gamuts "stretch" the bits over a broader region of colors, whereas smaller gamuts concentrate these bits within a narrow region.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] A similar, yet not as dramatic concentration of bit depth occurs with Adobe RGB (1998) versus sRGB, except in three dimensions rather than one.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] The Adobe RGB (1998) color space occupies roughly 40% more volume than the sRGB color space, which concludes that one would only be exploiting 70% of the available bit depth if the colors in Adobe RGB (1998) are unnecessary.
[src:srgb-colorspace/adobe-rgb-color-space] On the contrary, one may have plenty of "spare" bits if using a 16-bit image, thus negating any reduction due to the choice of working space.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] In 2005, Digital Cinema Initiatives, LLC in Hollywood, California released the *Digital Cinema System Specification version 1.0*, which defined the colorimetry of what would become known as the DCI-P3 color space.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] According to section 8.3.4 in the specification, the blue primary color is the same as Rec.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] 709, sRGB, and Adobe RGB, with a dominant wavelength of 464.2 nm.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] The red primary is a deeper red than sRGB and Adobe RGB, as it emits a longer dominant wavelength at 614.9 nm.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] The red primary is also farther from the white point (being technically an imaginary color, as it is negligibly outside of the spectral locus in the chromaticity diagram), implying that it is more chromatic than the red-orange primary of sRGB.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] The most significant difference is the green primary, which is much closer to the spectral locus than either sRGB or Adobe RGB.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] DCI-P3's green primary has a dominant wavelength of 544.2 nm.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Adobe RGB's green primary is more bluish with a dominant wavelength of 534.7 nm. sRGB's green primary is more yellowish at 549.1 nm.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] DCI-P3 covers 53.6% of the CIE 1931 chromaticity diagram (see inset image), which describes the color gamut of human color vision.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] A smaller, practical gamut for comparison is the Pointer's gamut, which consists of diffusely reflecting surface colors.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] DCI-P3 covers 86.9% of Pointer's gamut, while in comparison, Rec.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] While DCI-P3 was developed by the Digital Cinema Initiatives (DCI) organization, many of the relevant technical standards are published by the Society of Motion Picture and Television Engineers (SMPTE) such as **SMPTE EG 432-1** and **SMPTE RP 431-2**.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] On November 10, 2010, SMPTE published SMPTE EG 432-1:2010, which includes a variant of the color space using a D65 white point (about 6503.51 K) instead of the ~6300 K white point of DCI-P3.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] On April 6, 2011, SMPTE published SMPTE RP 431-2:2011 which defines the reference viewing environment.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Display P3 / P3-D65 (SDR) are supported in CSS Color Level 4 on Safari since 2017 (version 10.1) and Google Chrome since March 2023 (version 111) browsers.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Initially, DCI-P3 was available with theatrical xenon-arc projection systems.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] This emerging technology presented challenges for filmmakers working with digital media on desktop workstations—that is, how to accurately view the colorspace of the theatrical viewing environment during the production and post-production process.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Created by the Digital Cinema Initiative, DCI-P3 is designed for viewing in a fully darkened theater environment.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] The projection system uses a simple 2.6 gamma curve, the nominal white luminance is 48 cd/m2 (14ftL), and the white point is based on a projector with a xenon bulb, for a correlated color temperature (CCT) of ~6300 K.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] It is incorrect to refer to this as "D63" as this white point is not a CIE standard illuminant, and is not on the Planckian locus.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Instead, the white point is slightly greener.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] This resulted from optimizing for best light output with the xenon arc lamp projectors commonly used in theaters.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] P3-DCI primaries were formally defined in SMPTE RP 431-2.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] When mastering content utilizing a display or projector in P3 color space, users have the option of using an output transform to DCI-P3 D60-sim which matches the nominal white point of the ACES color spaces.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Apple Inc. developed displays using the P3 primaries, creating the corresponding Display P3 color space, also known as P3-D65.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] While it uses standard P3 RGB primaries, the white point is D65 instead of the DCI ~6300 K white point.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] The D65 white point is the existing standard for common sRGB and devices (Adobe RGB also uses D65).
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] While the original Display P3 used an sRGB transfer curve (approximately equivalent to a gamma of 2.2), the specification was later updated to also support PQ and HLG transfer functions, but the PQ variant was subsequently deprecated.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Display P3's gamut is approximately 50% larger than sRGB in volume and 25% in surface.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Many smartphones, including Apple iPhone (since iPhone 7) and Google Pixel (since Pixel 8), support capturing wide color gamut photos using P3-D65 primaries.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Any such photos captured by iPhone and Android camera apps are tagged with the Display P3 ICC profile.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Netflix HDR video production deliverables commonly use P3-D65 primaries in conjunction with the PQ transfer curve.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] P3-D65 primaries were formally defined in SMPTE EG 432-1.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Canon created an expanded gamut color space they call **DCI-P3+** using the same ~6300 K white point as DCI-P3.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Otherwise, P3+ has no relation to DCI-P3 nor the Digital Cinema Initiative.
[src:srgb-colorspace/dci-p3] Unlike the DCI-P3 color space, which defines an actual display technology, Canon's DCI-P3+ color space uses imaginary primaries which cannot be realized by any physical display technology.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] where the non-negative real input value $V_{\text{in}}$ is raised to the power $\gamma$ and multiplied by the constant *A* to get the output value $V_{\text{out}}$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In the common case of *A* = 1, inputs and outputs are typically in the range 0–1.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Gamma encoding of images is used to optimize the usage of bits when encoding an image, or bandwidth used to transport an image, by taking advantage of the non-linear manner in which humans perceive light and color.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] If images are not gamma-encoded, they allocate too many bits or too much bandwidth to highlights that humans cannot differentiate, and too few bits or too little bandwidth to shadow values that humans are sensitive to and would require more bits/bandwidth to maintain the same visual quality.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Gamma encoding of floating-point images is not required (and may be counterproductive), because the floating-point format already provides a piecewise linear approximation of a logarithmic curve.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Although gamma encoding was developed originally to compensate for the brightness characteristics of cathode-ray tube (CRT) displays, that is not its main purpose or advantage in modern systems.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In CRT displays, the light intensity varies nonlinearly with the electron-gun voltage.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Altering the input signal by gamma compression can cancel this nonlinearity, such that the output picture has the intended luminance.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] However, the gamma characteristics of the display device do not play a factor in the gamma encoding of images and video.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] They need gamma encoding to maximize the visual quality of the signal, regardless of the gamma characteristics of the display device.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The similarity of CRT physics to the inverse of gamma encoding needed for video transmission was a combination of coincidence and engineering, which simplified the electronics in early television sets.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Photographic film has a much greater ability to record fine differences in shade than can be reproduced on printed paper.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Similarly, most video screens are not capable of displaying the range of brightnesses (dynamic range) that can be captured by typical electronic cameras.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] For this reason, considerable artistic effort is invested in choosing the reduced form in which the original image should be presented.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The gamma correction, or contrast selection, is part of the photographic repertoire used to adjust the reproduced image.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Analogously, digital cameras record light using electronic sensors that usually respond linearly.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In the process of rendering linear raw data to conventional RGB data (e.g. for storage into JPEG image format), color space transformations and rendering transformations will be performed.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In particular, almost all standard RGB color spaces and file formats use a non-linear encoding (a gamma compression) of the intended intensities of the primary colors of the photographic reproduction.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In addition, the intended reproduction is almost always nonlinearly related to the measured scene intensities, via a tone reproduction nonlinearity.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The concept of gamma can be applied to any nonlinear relationship.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] That is, gamma can be visualized as the slope of the input–output curve when plotted on logarithmic axes.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] For a power-law curve, this slope is constant, but the idea can be extended to any type of curve, in which case gamma (strictly speaking, "point gamma") is defined as the slope of the curve in any particular region.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] When a photographic film is exposed to light, the result of the exposure can be represented on a graph showing log of exposure on the horizontal axis, and density, or negative log of transmittance, on the vertical axis.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] For a given film formulation and processing method, this curve is its characteristic or Hurter–Driffield curve.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Since both axes use logarithmic units, the slope of the linear section of the curve is called the gamma of the film.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Negative film typically has a gamma less than 1; positive film (slide film, reversal film) typically has a gamma with absolute value greater than 1.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Output to CRT-based television receivers and monitors does not usually require further gamma correction.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The standard video signals that are transmitted or stored in image files incorporate gamma compression matching the gamma expansion of the CRT (although it is not the exact inverse).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] For television signals, gamma values are fixed and defined by the analog video standards.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] CCIR System M, associated with NTSC color, use gamma 2.2; systems B/G, H, I, D/K, K1, L, M, and N, associated with PAL or SECAM color use gamma 2.8.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In most computer display systems, images are encoded with a gamma of about 0.45 and decoded with the reciprocal gamma of 2.2.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] A notable exception, until the release of Mac OS X 10.6 (Snow Leopard) in September 2009, were Macintosh computers, which encoded with a gamma of 0.55 and decoded with a gamma of 1.8.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In any case, binary data in still image files (such as JPEG) are explicitly encoded (that is, they carry gamma-encoded values, not linear intensities), as are motion picture files (such as MPEG).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The system can optionally further manage both cases, through color management, if a better match to the output device gamma is required.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The sRGB color space standard used with most cameras, PCs, and printers does not use a simple power-law nonlinearity as above, but has a decoding gamma value near 2.2 over much of its range, as shown in the plot to the right/above.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Below a compressed value of 0.04045 or a linear intensity of 0.00313, the curve is linear (encoded value proportional to intensity), so *γ* = 1.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The dashed black curve behind the red curve is a standard *γ* = 2.2 power-law curve, for comparison.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Gamma correction in computers is used, for example, to display a gamma = 1.8 Apple picture correctly on a gamma = 2.2 PC monitor by changing the image gamma.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Another usage is equalizing of the individual color-channel gammas to correct for monitor discrepancies.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Some picture formats allow an image's intended gamma (of transformations between encoded image samples and light output) to be stored as metadata, facilitating automatic gamma correction.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The PNG specification includes the gAMA chunk for this purpose and with formats such as JPEG and TIFF the Exif Gamma tag can be used.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Some formats can specify the ICC profile which includes a transfer function.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] These features have historically caused problems, especially on the web.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] This made it impossible for PNG images to simultaneously match HTML or untagged JPG colors on every device.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] This situation has since improved, as most major browsers now support the gamma setting (or lack of it).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] A *gamma characteristic* is a power-law relationship that approximates the relationship between the encoded luma in a television system and the actual desired image luminance.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] With this nonlinear relationship, equal steps in encoded luminance correspond roughly to subjectively equal steps in brightness.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Ebner and Fairchild used an exponent of 0.43 to convert linear intensity into lightness (luma) for neutrals; the reciprocal, approximately 2.33 (quite close to the 2.2 figure cited for a typical display subsystem), was found to provide approximately optimal perceptual encoding of grays.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The following illustration shows the difference between a scale with linearly-increasing encoded luminance signal (linear gamma-compressed luma input) and a scale with linearly-increasing intensity scale (linear luminance output).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] On most displays (those with gamma of about 2.2), one can observe that the linear-intensity scale has a large jump in perceived brightness between the intensity values 0.0 and 0.1, while the steps at the higher end of the scale are hardly perceptible.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The gamma-encoded scale, which has a nonlinearly-increasing intensity, will show much more even steps in perceived brightness.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] A CRT, for example, converts a video signal to light in a nonlinear way, because the electron gun's intensity (brightness) as a function of applied video voltage is nonlinear.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] For simplicity, consider the example of a monochrome CRT.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In this case, when a video signal of 0.5 (representing a mid-gray) is fed to the display, the intensity or brightness is about 0.22 (resulting in a mid-gray, about 22% the intensity of white).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Pure black (0.0) and pure white (1.0) are the only shades that are unaffected by gamma.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] To compensate for this effect, the inverse transfer function (gamma correction) is sometimes applied to the video signal so that the end-to-end response is linear.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In other words, the transmitted signal is deliberately distorted so that, after it has been distorted again by the display device, the viewer sees the correct brightness.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] where *V*c is the corrected voltage, and *V*s is the source voltage, for example, from an image sensor that converts photocharge linearly to a voltage.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] A color CRT receives three video signals (red, green, and blue) and in general each color has its own value of gamma, denoted *γ**R*, *γ**G* or *γ**B*.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] However, in simple display systems, a single value of *γ* is used for all three colors.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Other display devices have different values of gamma: for example, a Game Boy Advance display has a gamma between 3 and 4 depending on lighting conditions.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In LCDs such as those on laptop computers, the relation between the signal voltage *V*s and the intensity *I* is very nonlinear and cannot be described with gamma value.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] However, such displays apply a correction onto the signal voltage in order to approximately get a standard *γ* = 2.5 behavior.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In NTSC television recording, *γ* = 2.2.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The power-law function, or its inverse, has a slope of infinity at zero.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] This leads to problems in converting from and to a gamma colorspace.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] For this reason most formally defined colorspaces such as sRGB will define a straight-line segment near zero and add raising *x* + *K* (where *K* is a constant) to a power so the curve has continuous slope.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] This straight line does not represent what the CRT does, but does make the rest of the curve more closely match the effect of ambient light on the CRT.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In such expressions the exponent is *not* the gamma; for instance, the sRGB function uses a power of 2.4 in it, but more closely resembles a power-law function with an exponent of 2.2, without a linear portion.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In a correctly calibrated system, each component will have a specified gamma for its input and/or output encodings.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Stages may change the gamma to correct for different requirements, and finally the output device will do gamma decoding or correction as needed, to get to a linear intensity domain.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In a typical system, for example from camera through JPEG file to display, the role of gamma correction will involve several cooperating parts.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The camera encodes its rendered image into the JPEG file using one of the standard gamma values such as 2.2, for storage and transmission.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The display computer may use a color management engine to convert to a different color space (such as older Macintosh's *γ* = 1.8 color space) before putting pixel values into its video memory.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The monitor may do its own gamma correction to match the CRT gamma to that used by the video system.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Coordinating the components via standard interfaces with default standard gamma values makes it possible to get such system properly configured.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] This procedure is useful for making a monitor display images approximately correctly, on systems in which profiles are not used (for example, the Firefox browser prior to version 3.0 and many others) or in systems that assume untagged source images are in the sRGB colorspace.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In the test pattern, the intensity of each solid color bar is intended to be the average of the intensities in the surrounding dotted dither; therefore, ideally, the solid areas and the dithers should appear equally bright in a system properly adjusted to the indicated gamma.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Normally a graphics card has contrast and brightness control and a transmissive LCD monitor has contrast, brightness, and backlight control.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Graphics card and monitor contrast and brightness have an influence on effective gamma, and should not be changed after gamma correction is completed.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The top two bars of the test image help to set correct contrast and brightness values.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] There are eight three-digit numbers in each bar.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] A good monitor with proper calibration shows the six numbers on the right in both bars; a cheap monitor shows only four numbers.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Given a desired display-system gamma, if the observer sees the same brightness in the checkered part and in the homogeneous part of every colored area, then the gamma correction is approximately correct.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In many cases the gamma correction values for the primary colors are slightly different.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Setting the color temperature or white point is the next step in monitor adjustment.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Before gamma correction the desired gamma and color temperature should be set using the monitor controls.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Using the controls for gamma, contrast and brightness, the gamma correction on an LCD can only be done for one specific vertical viewing angle, which implies one specific horizontal line on the monitor, at one specific brightness and contrast level.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] An ICC profile allows one to adjust the monitor for several brightness levels.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The quality (and price) of the monitor determines how much deviation of this operating point still gives a satisfactory gamma correction.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Twisted nematic (TN) displays with 6-bit color depth per primary color have lowest quality.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In-plane switching (IPS) displays with typically 8-bit color depth are better.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Good monitors have 10-bit color depth, have hardware color management and allow hardware calibration with a tristimulus colorimeter.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Often a 6bit plus FRC panel is sold as 8bit and a 8bit plus FRC panel is sold as 10bit.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] FRC is no true replacement for more bits.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The 24-bit and 32-bit color depth formats have 8 bits per primary color.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] With Microsoft Windows 7 and above the user can set the gamma correction through the display color calibration tool dccw.exe or other programs.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] These programs create an ICC profile file and load it as default.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Increase the gamma slider in the dccw program until the last colored area, often the green color, has the same brightness in checkered and homogeneous area.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Use the color balance or individual colors gamma correction sliders in the gamma correction programs to adjust the two other colors.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Some old graphics card drivers do not load the color Look Up Table correctly after waking up from standby or hibernate mode and show wrong gamma.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In this case update the graphics card driver.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] On some operating systems running the X Window System, one can set the gamma correction factor (applied to the existing gamma value) by issuing the command `xgamma -gamma 0.9` for setting gamma correction factor to 0.9, and `xgamma` for querying current value of that factor (the default is 1.0).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In macOS systems, the gamma and other related screen calibrations are made through the System Preferences.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In addition to scaling, the problem also applies to other forms of downsampling (scaling down), such as chroma subsampling in JPEG's gamma-enabled Y′CbCr.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] WebP solves this problem by calculating the chroma averages in linear space then converting back to a gamma-enabled space; an iterative solution is used for larger images.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The same *sharp YUV* (formerly *smart YUV*) code is used in sjpeg and optionally in AVIF.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Kornelski provides a simpler approximation by luma-based weighted average.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Alpha compositing, color gradients, and 3D rendering are also affected by this issue.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Paradoxically, when upsampling (scaling up) an image, the result processed in a "wrong" (non-physical) gamma color space is often more aesthetically pleasing.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] This is because resampling filters with negative lobes like Mitchell–Netravali and Lanczos create ringing artifacts linearly even though human perception is non-linear and better approximated by gamma.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The term intensity refers strictly to the amount of light that is emitted per unit of time and per unit of surface, in units of lux.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Note, however, that in many fields of science this quantity is called luminous exitance, as opposed to luminous intensity, which is a different quantity.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] These distinctions, however, are largely irrelevant to gamma compression, which is applicable to any sort of normalized linear intensity-like scale.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] One contrasts relative luminance in the sense of color (no gamma compression) with luma in the sense of video (with gamma compression), and denote relative luminance by *Y* and luma by *Y*′, the prime symbol (′) denoting gamma compression.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Note that luma is not directly calculated from luminance, it is the (somewhat arbitrary) weighted sum of gamma-compressed RGB components.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Likewise, *brightness* is sometimes applied to various measures, including light levels, though it more properly applies to a subjective visual attribute.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Gamma correction is a type of power-law function whose exponent is the Greek letter gamma (*γ*).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] It should not be confused with the mathematical Gamma function.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] The lower case gamma, *γ*, is a parameter of the former; the upper case letter, Γ, is the name of (and symbol used for) the latter (as in Γ(*x*)).
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] To use the word "function" in conjunction with gamma correction, one may avoid confusion by saying "generalized power-law function".
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Without context, a value labeled gamma might be either the encoding or the decoding value.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] Caution must be taken to correctly interpret the value as that to be applied-to-compensate or to be compensated-by-applying its inverse.
[src:srgb-colorspace/gamma-correction] In common parlance, in many occasions the decoding value (as 2.2) is employed as if it were the encoding value, instead of its inverse (1/2.2 in this case), which is the *real* value that must be applied to encode gamma.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The standard is freely available at the ITU website, and that document should be used as the authoritative reference.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Recommendation ITU-R BT.709-6 defines a common image format (CIF) where picture characteristics are independent of the frame rate.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The image is 1920x1080 pixels, for a total pixel count of 2,073,600 and a 16:9 aspect ratio.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] BT.709-6 specifies the following possible frame rates and pixel scanning order.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] These combinations match the frame rate used for theatrical motion pictures.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] There are no fractional rates as PAL and SECAM did not have the pull-down issue of NTSC.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] These combinations offer compatibility with earlier "60 Hz" TV standards, as NTSC.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Here again, the fractional rates are for compatibility with legacy NTSC pull-down rates.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Cameras and monitors may use any of these modes.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Video captured in progressive mode can be recorded, broadcast, or streamed in progressive or progressive segmented frame modes.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Video captured using an interlaced mode must be distributed as interlace unless a de-interlace process is applied in post production.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] In cases where a progressive captured image is distributed in segmented frame mode, segment/field frequency must be twice the frame rate.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Thus 30/PsF has the same field rate as 60/I.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Colors in the BT.709 standard are described according to the RGB color model, namely as mixtures of three primaries—red (R), green (G) and blue (B)—in reference to specified white point (W).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] In the BT.709 standard, a color value is conceptually represented by three numbers $(E_{R},E_{G},E_{B})$ between 0 and 1, where 0 means the absence of the corresponding primary color and 1 means the maximum intensity that the color space can represent.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] If these numbers are interpreted as Cartesian coordinates in a three-dimensional space, the representable colors correspond to points in an axis-aligned cube of side 1, with corner $(0,0,0)$ representing the color black and $(1,1,1)$ representing the maximum-brightness white.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] More generally, points along the cube's diagonal represent shades of grey.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The white point coordinates above define this white color as being CIE illuminant D65 for 2° standard observer.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The coordinates $(E_{R},E_{G},E_{B})$ are supposed to be proportional to the physical intensity of each primary, namely emitted or received light power per unit of area.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] For efficiency reasons, the standard specifies a non-linear transformation of each component signal, resulting in $(E'_{R},E'_{G},E'_{B})$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] In order to display the colors on a device, such as a HDTV monitor, the encoded values $(E'_{R},E'_{G},E'_{B})$ should be converted back to physical intensities of the primaries.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The Rec.709 transfer characteristics is defined in terms of a reference opto-electronic transfer characteristic function.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] However, the BT.709 standard does not specify a corresponding reference electro-optical transfer characteristic function (sometimes referred as "display gamma").
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] In practice, display gamma depends on various factors such as the capabilities of the monitor, the viewing conditions, and desired visual effects (such as contrast or saturation stretching).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] A suggested corresponding reference electro-optical transfer characteristic function for flat panel displays used in HDTV studio production has been specified in ITU-R BT.1886 and EBU Tech 3320.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The BT.709 standard also defines an alternative representation of colors by three coordinates $(E'_{Y},E'_{\mathit {CB}},E'_{\mathit {CR}})$ which are linear combinations of the (non-linear) RGB coordinates $(E'_{R},E'_{G},E'_{B})$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The value $E'_{Y}$ is called "luminance" in the standard, and is roughly an approximation of the CIE Y coordinate (which is presumed to measure the perceptual brightness of the color) modified by the non-linear function above.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] However, since $E'_{Y}$ is computed from the non-linear RGB components, this equivalence is correct only for shades of gray.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The other two coordinates indicate the "blueness" and "redness" of the color's hue.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] This quantization shall be performed by simple scaling and rounding, so as to yield integers that span a proper subset of the n -bit integers.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The ${\mbox{round}}$ function should round the argument to the nearest integer, with ties rounded up (that is, ${\mbox{round}}(3.4999)=3$ and ${\mbox{round}}(3.5000)=4$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] These quantization formulas are the same as those defined in ITU-R BT.601.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] It follows that in limited range 8-bit R'G'B' the color black is represented as (16,16,16) while white is (235,235,235).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Quantized color coordinates outside the nominal ranges above are allowed, but typically they would be clamped for broadcast or for display (except for Superwhite and xvYCC).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] However, in the limited range the 8-bit values 0 and 255 and the 10 bit values 0..3 and 1020..1023 are reserved for timing marks (SAV and EAV) and cannot appear in color data.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The creation of a worldwide HDTV standard was approved in 1989 by the Comité consultatif international pour la radio (CCIR) as "Recommendation XA/11 MOD F".
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The first official version of the standard was approved in 1990 by the CCIR, under the name "Recommendation 709".
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The CCIR became the ITU-R in 1992, and released a new version of the standard (BT.709-1) in November 1993.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] These early versions still left many unanswered questions, and the lack of consensus toward a worldwide HDTV standard was evident.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] So much so, some early HDTV systems such as 1035i30 and 1152i25 were still a part of the standard as late as 2002 in BT.709-5.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The most recent version is BT.709-6 released in 2015.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The standard strictly determined the picture size but offered several options for the pixel scanning order and frame rate.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] This flexibility allows BT.709 to become the worldwide standard for HDTV.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] This allows manufacturers to create a single television set or display for all markets world-wide.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The BT.709 standard calls the non-linear encoding of $(ER,EG,EB)$ to $(E'R,E'G,E'B)$ the optical electrical transfer function because it was meant to resemble the conversion of light intensity into analog electrical signals implemented by older non-digital cameras.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] It had long been known that a non-linear encoding of colors was more efficient than a linear one because human vision is more sensitive to brightness changes at low light levels.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] That conversion was commonly specified as a power law $V=L^{\gamma }$ with exponent $\gamma$ near 0.5 (hence the common names "gamma correction" or "camera gamma" for the encoding function).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The BT.709 encoding function OETF is close to a power law with exponent near 1/2.0.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The BT.709 encoding function is not a simple power law because the latter has infinite slope at the origin, which emphasizes camera noise and is problematic for analog-to-digital converters.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Thus the standard opted for a piecewise function that combines a simple linear function $V=a\,L$ for low light levels and a shifted power law $((L+c)/(1+c))^{\gamma }$ for larger values.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Conversion between different standards of video frame rates and color encoding has always been a challenge for content producers distributing through regions with different standards and requirements.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The BT.709 red and blue primaries are the same as the EBU Tech 3213 (PAL) primaries.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The yG coordinate too is the same, while xG is halfway between EBU Tech 3213's xG and SMPTE C's xG.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The resulting BT.709 color space is almost identical to that of the BT.601-6 used by PAL and SMPTE C, and covers 35.9% of the CIE 1931 color space.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] It also covers 33.24% of the CIE 1976 u’v’ space and 33.5% of the CIE 1931 xy diagram.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The vast legacy library of standard-definition programs and content presents further challenges.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] NTSC, PAL, and SECAM are all interlaced formats in a 4:3 aspect ratio, and at a relatively low resolution.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Scaling them up to HD resolution with a 16:9 aspect ratio presents a number of challenges.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] First is the potential for distracting motion artifacts due to interlaced video content.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The solution is to either up-convert only to an interlaced BT.709 format at the same field rate, and scale the fields independently, or use motion processing to remove the inter-field motion and deinterlace, creating progressive frames.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] In the latter case, motion processing can introduce artifacts and can be slow to process.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Second is the issue of accommodating the SD 4:3 aspect ratio into the HD 16:9 frame.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Cropping the top and/or bottom of the standard-definition frame may or may not work, depending on if the composition allows it and if there are graphics or titles that would be cut off.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Alternately, pillar-boxing can show the entire 4:3 image by leaving black borders on the left and right.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Sometimes this black is filled with a stretched and blurred form of the image.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] In addition, the SMPTE C RGB primaries used in North American standard definition are different than those of BT.709 (SMPTE C is commonly referred to as NTSC, however it is a different set of primaries and a different white point than the NTSC 1953).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The red and blue primaries for PAL and SECAM are the same as BT.709, with a change in the green primary.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Converting the image precisely requires a LUT (lookup table) or a color managed workflow to convert the colors to the new colorspace.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] However, in practice this is often ignored, except in mpv, because even if the player is color managed (most of them are not, including VLC), it can see BT.709 or BT.2020 primaries only.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] When encoding *Y’C*B*C*R video, BT.709 creates gamma-encoded luma (*Y’*) using matrix coefficients 0.2126, 0.7152, and 0.0722 (together they add to 1).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Although worldwide agreement on a single R’G’B’ system was achieved with Rec.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] 709, adoption of different luma coefficients (as those are derived from primaries and white point) for *Y’C*B*C*R requires the use of different luma-chroma decoding for standard definition and high definition.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] These problems can be handled with video processing software which can be slow, or hardware solutions which allow for realtime conversion, and often with quality improvements.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] A more ideal solution is to go back to original film elements for projects that originated on film.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Due to the legacy issues of international distribution, many television programs that shot on film used a traditional negative cutting process, and then had a single film master that could be telecined for different formats.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] These projects can re-telecine their cut negative masters to a BT.709 master at a reasonable cost, and gain the benefit of the full resolution of film.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] In this case, to enjoy the benefits of the film original would entail much higher costs to conform the film originals to a new HD master.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] sRGB was created after the early development of Rec.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] The creators of sRGB chose to use the same primaries and white point as Rec.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] 709, but changed the tone response curve (sometimes referred to as gamma) to better suit the intended use in offices and brighter conditions than television viewing in a dark living room.
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] 709 and sRGB share the same primary chromaticities and white point chromaticity; however, sRGB is explicitly output (display) referred with an equivalent gamma of 2.2 (the actual function is also piecewise to avoid near black issues).
[src:srgb-colorspace/rec-709] Display P3 uses sRGB EOTF with its linear segment, a change of that segment from 709 is needed by either using parametric curve encoding of ICC v4 or by using slope limit.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The sRGB standard uses the same color primaries and white point as the ITU-R BT.709 standard for HDTV, but a different transfer function (or gamma) compatible with the era's CRT displays, and assumes a viewing environment closer to typical home and office viewing conditions.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Matching the behavior of PC video cards and CRT displays greatly aided sRGB's popularity.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] By the 1970s, most computers translated 8-bit digital data fairly linearly to a signal that was sent to a video monitor.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] However video monitors and TVs produced a brightness that was not linear with the input signal, roughly a power law with an exponent between 2 and 3.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The exponent was commonly denoted with the letter $\gamma$ , hence the common name "gamma correction" for this function.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] This design has the benefit of displaying an image with much less visual artifacts, as it places the digital values closer together near black and further apart near white (where changes in brightness are less visible).
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] This gamma varied according to CRT manufacturers, but was normalized in 1993 for use in HDTV systems, as the ITU BT.709 standard.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The BT.709 standard specified OETF with a linear section near zero, transitioning to a shifted power law with exponent 1/0.45 ≈ 2.22...
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] sRGB was created a few years later by Hewlett-Packard and Microsoft.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] It was meant to describe the decoding function of most CRT computer monitors used with Windows operating systems at the time, which was still different from that assumed by BT.709.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The first draft of the standard was published in 1996.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] A fourth draft, still incomplete, is available online.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Like the BT.709, the sRGB OETF was defined as a linear section near zero that transitions to a shifted power law.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The standard does specify EOTF as 2.2 pure gamma with veiling glare term, but glare is a property of the display and should not be added manually to the digital signal.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Actually using the sRGB standard became important as computer graphics software started to calculate in linear light levels in the late 1990s, and needed to use sRGB to convert from and to the common 8-bit image standards.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Images such as shown here became popular for adjusting a CRT monitor to correctly display sRGB.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Amendment 1 to IEC 61966-2-1:1999, approved in 2003, also defines a YCbCr encoding called sYCC and a conversion to more than 8 bits called bg-sRGB.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The scRGB standard also tries to extend sRGB to more bits.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] An sRGB image file contains R′G′B′ values for each pixel.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] 0.0 is "black" while 1.0 is the intensity of a color primary needed by "white".
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] These floating-point values are derived from the file data; for a typical 8-bit-per-channel image the bytes are divided by 255.0.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The mapping from these values to intensity is a non-linear transfer function which is the combination of a linear function at low brightness values and a displaced power law for the rest of the range.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] This function is quite close to $R'^{2.2}$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] However, for low values near 0.04045 the difference is perceptible; without that linear part, with an 8-bit depth, the darkest ~20 levels would all map to extremely tiny changes in linear light — differences the display couldn't distinguish after rounding.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The linear section also compensates for viewing glare term in the EOTF by making small signal darker than it is with a pure 0.45-power function.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] If needed by the file format, values greater than 1.0 can be used (the results will also be greater than 1.0), and values less than 0.0 can be converted as -*f*(-*x*).
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] These functions are similar to those of BT.709, but the values are noticeably different.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Because of the rounding of the parameters, they have small discontinuities at the transition between the linear and non-linear part, on the order of 10−8, and they are not precise inverses of each other.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] These errors are too small to matter in practical situations.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] In practice many pieces of software use different close-by values (see below), or ignore the linear section, or use a plain gamma 2.2 function.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The change in the images is almost imperceptible, however it will make noticeable seams when differently-converted images are overlapped, and mismatched translations back and forth accumulate color shifts.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Many operating systems and programs send 8-bit sRGB images directly to video memory and assume this produces the correct levels.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] A shifted power law curve that passes through (1,1) is $y=\left({\frac {x+C}{1+C}}\right)^{\gamma }$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] A straight line that passes through (0,0), is $y=x/A$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The transition from the linear section to the power law section should be continuous (without a sudden step) and smooth (without a sudden change of slope).
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The first draft of the sRGB standard chose $\gamma =2.4$ and then computed $C=0.055$ so that the value at $x=0.4$ was near $x^{2.2}$ .
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] These values, rounded to 5 digits as shown, are still incorrectly given in some publications.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] However, the sRGB draft standard rounded A to $12.92$ , resulting in a small discontinuity in the curve.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The first official version of the standard was defined and published by the IEC in 1999.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] In this version, the rounded value of $A=12.92$ was retained, but the breakpoint X was redefined as $0.04045$ to make the curve approximately continuous.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] With these values, there is still a discontinuity in the slope, from $1/12.92$ just below the intersection to $1/12.70$ just above it.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The final standard also corrected some small rounding errors present in the draft.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The sRGB standard defines the chromaticities of the red, green, and blue primaries, the colors where one of the three channels is nonzero and the other two are zero.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The gamut of chromaticities that can be represented in sRGB is the color triangle defined by these primaries, which are set such that the range of colors inside the triangle is well within the range of colors visible to a human with normal trichromatic vision.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] As with any RGB color space, for non-negative values of R, G, and B it is not possible to represent colors outside this triangle.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] 709), which are somewhat different from those for older color TV systems (Rec.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] These values were chosen to approximate the color of consumer CRT phosphors at that time.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The sRGB standard specifies the colors by providing a matrix that converts the linear values to CIE XYZ perceptual color coordinates with the 2° standard colorimetric observer.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The inverse conversion, from CIE XYZ to (linear) RGB, is obtained by inverting the matrix above to a suitable numerical accuracy.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] This is usually true but some color spaces use 100 or other values (such as in CIELAB, when using specified white points).
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The assumed ambient CCT differs from that of the BT.709 standard illuminant (D65), which is still retained for the screen white point.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Using D50 for both would have made the white point of most photographic paper appear excessively blue.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The other parameters, such as the luminance level, are representative of a typical CRT monitor.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] For optimal results, the ICC recommends using the encoding viewing environment (i.e., dim, diffuse lighting) rather than the less-stringent typical viewing environment.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] When the sRGB values are sent over to the display, e.g. over HDMI, you don't add any glare offset or compensate it in software, the display and the viewing environment naturally produce this small flare.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Most file formats that use sRGB store 8-bit integers.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Usually these are converted from 8 bits by dividing by 255.0, and converted to 8 bits by multiplying by 255 and rounding.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] However some software converts to 8 bits by multiplying by 256 and rounding down.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Higher-quality software often uses dithering when writing so that color banding is hidden.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Annex G of the 2003 amendment of the sRGB standard describes an alternative encoding of color values, called **bg-sRGB**, that is recommended when the number of bits per channel is 10 or more.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] In this case 0.0 is mapped to a *black point* K and 1.0 is mapped to a *white point* W, with all other values interpreted linearly.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The 12-bit scRGB format does something similar, with *K* = 1024 and *W* = 2304.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Allowing numbers greater than 1.0 allows high dynamic range images, and negative numbers allows colors outside the gamut triangle.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Due to the standardization of sRGB on the Internet, on computers, and on printers, many low- to medium-end consumer digital cameras and scanners use sRGB as the default (or only available) working color space.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] If the color space of an image is unknown and encoded with 8 bits in each channel, the sRGB encoding can be assumed.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Due to programmers misunderstanding the meaning of "gamma" some image files that claim they contain a gamma of 1.0 should also be assumed to be sRGB.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] As the sRGB gamut mostly meets or exceeds the gamut of a low-end inkjet printer, an sRGB image is often regarded as satisfactory for home printing.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The sRGB color space is sometimes avoided by high-end print publishing professionals because its color gamut is not big enough, especially in the blue-green colors, to include all the colors that can be reproduced in CMYK printing.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Images intended for professional printing via a fully color-managed workflow (e.g. prepress output) sometimes use another color space such as Adobe RGB (1998), which accommodates a wider gamut and CMYK color space like Fogra39.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The two dominant programming interfaces for 3D graphics, OpenGL and Direct3D, have both incorporated support for the sRGB gamma curve.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] OpenGL supports textures with sRGB gamma encoded color components (first introduced with EXT_texture_sRGB extension, added to the core in OpenGL 2.1) and rendering into sRGB gamma encoded framebuffers (first introduced with EXT_framebuffer_sRGB extension, added to the core in OpenGL 3.0).
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Correct mipmapping and interpolation of sRGB gamma textures has direct hardware support in texturing units of most modern GPUs (for example nVidia GeForce 8 performs conversion from 8-bit texture to linear values before interpolating those values), and does not have any performance penalty.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] A lookup table may be used to efficiently convert sRGB to other color spaces.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] The International Color Consortium (ICC) has published color profiles for this purpose, which are widely used.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] There are several variants, including ICCmax, version 4, and version 2.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Version 4 is generally recommended, but version 2 is still commonly used and is the most compatible with other software including browsers.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] However, inconsistencies have been pointed out between those ICC profiles and the IEC sRGB standard.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] In particular, version 2 of the ICC profile specification does not implement the piecewise parametric curve encoding ("para") as specified by the IEC sRGB standard, and has to implement the sRGB transfer function using a one-dimensional lookup table.
[src:srgb-colorspace/srgb] Some implementations approximate the transfer function as 2.2 gamma, with no linear portion, called "simplified sRGB".
